In this thread I will summarize the @artofmanliness article on the importance of heavy carrying exercise (in a similar fashion to farmer's walks) artofmanliness.com/articles/‚Ä¶ Even men who are quite strong (and able to deadlift over 4 plates) still struggle to carry heavy objects.

3. Carrying tends to be far more functional in day-to-day life.

4. Carrying is a compound exercise and leads to improved musculature of the core, hips, trapezoids, neck, and others.

5. Carrying correlates to improved conditioning (aka CNS gains and improved work capacity)

Lifting Strength =/= Carrying Strength

1. Carrying heavy weights requires a great deal of better balance and stability, especially when carrying a non-symmetrical object.

(Core Strength!)

2. Carrying requires FAR more effort than simply lifting an object and putting it down

8. Friction from carrying heavy objects will toughen and strengthen your skin (this, of course, refers only to shoulder or sandbag carries).

So, when and how should you do these carrying exercises?

The article suggests doing them once weekly and using "comfortable weight"...

6. Carrying GREATLY improves your stability. This practically means you will be far harder to fall and that you will physically feel stronger and more stable.

7. Carrying improves your squeezing strength potential and teaches you to stay flexed/tensed during lifting.

... because they can't be done in most gyms. This does give you a good excuse to go for a saturday hike or a very early morning workout in the park. Be careful! Sandbag carries does not mean that you have to use a sandbag - any uneven object works - stones, logs, filled backpacks

Farmer's walks are a classic and a staple in many good routines. They are easy to do in every gym - just pick up a heavy dumbbell or two and start walking at the end of your workout. You can also go for the over-the-head version.

Sandbag carries are a tad more tricky, ...

Rucking carries a big number of benefits, including improved posture, increased strength, and improved CARDIO - yep, rucking is the best cardio for the man that hates running or cycling. It also is far less stressful on your joints. I definitely recommend you give it a try.

So, this is it! To sum up again:

- Once weekly practice carrying different heavy objects in various manners
- Occasionally go rucking with a heavy backpack

That's it, this is an article I've enjoyed so I decided to type it out in a twitter-friendly format. See ya!
